            <div>
                <entry xml:id="L4af946fcdeb346a887dd9d9564c09196" n="12396">
                    <form>
                        <foreign xml:lang="gez">ሀልሀል</foreign>
                    </form>
                    <sense xml:id="Tmain" xml:lang="en" source="#traces">
                        <cit type="transcription" xml:lang="gez">
                            <t:quote xmlns:t="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"> halhal </t:quote>
                        </cit>
                        <gramGrp><pos expand="Substantivum">subst.</pos></gramGrp>
                        <cit type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                            <t:quote xmlns:t="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"> anklet </t:quote>
                        </cit>
                        <foreign xml:lang="gez">ወረሰዩ፡ ውስተ፡ ክሳዱ፡ ጋገ፡ ወርቅ፡ ወገብሩ፡ ሎቱ፡ ሀልሀላተ፡ ዘወርቅ፡ ውስተ፡
                            ፬እገሪሁ፡</foreign> ‘<cit type="translation" xml:lang="fr">
                            <t:quote xmlns:t="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"> ils lui avaient mis au
                                cou un collier d’or et lui avaient mis des anneaux d’or aux quatre
                                pattes </t:quote>
                        </cit>’ <bibl><ptr target="bm:Colin1990SynaxTerr"/><citedRange unit="page">
                                112 l. 4–5 (ed.); 113 l. 5–6 (tr.)</citedRange></bibl> (‘Il semble
                        que l’ethiopien ait transcrit purement et simplement le mot arabe خلخل en
                        l’affectant d’une marque de pluriel externe.’ <bibl><ptr target="bm:Colin1990SynaxTerr"/><citedRange unit="page"> 113 n.
                                2</citedRange></bibl>) <nd/> The word has been translated as an
                        “anklet” rather than a “ring”, as suggested by the editor. This is because
                        the above mentioned Arabic word actually means an “anklet” and indeed such
                        translation is more fitting to the context of the sentence. </sense>
                </entry>
